<task id="033" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r3">
  <metadata>
    <title>Add optional templateFilter prop to WorkspaceLayoutWizard</title>
    <phase>Phase C ŌĆö Workspace Pane</phase>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-hours>2</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>001</dependencies>
    <blocks>none</blocks>
    <tags>react, frontend, refactoring</tags>
    <rigor-hint>STANDARD</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Additive prop change to existing component. New file is the unit test only; modified files are net-existing. STANDARD rigor ŌĆö has constraints (FR-25 backwards compat is load-bearing) but the change surface is small and isolated to WorkspaceLayoutWizard package.</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>C</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Add an optional `templateFilter?: LayoutTemplateId[]` prop to the `WorkspaceLayoutWizard`
    component (likely in `App.tsx` or `steps/TemplateStep.tsx`). Default behavior (no prop passed)
    preserves backwards compatibility ŌĆö all 9 templates remain selectable for the standalone
    LegalWorkspace consumer per FR-25. When the prop IS passed (by SpaarkeAi's `WorkspacePaneMenu`
    in task 032), the template selector is restricted to the listed IDs. Implements FR-14 and the
    FR-25 backwards-compat invariant.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    React 19 + TypeScript developer making a careful additive prop change to a shared wizard.
    Bias toward zero behavior change when the prop is absent; clean filtering when it is present;
    unit tests covering both paths.
  </role>

  <goal>
    `WorkspaceLayoutWizard` accepts an optional `templateFilter?: LayoutTemplateId[]` prop.
    When absent ŌåÆ all 9 templates are rendered in the TemplateStep (current behavior preserved).
    When present ŌåÆ only the listed templates are rendered. A unit test covers both paths. The
    standalone LegalWorkspace continues to invoke the wizard without `templateFilter` and sees
    all 9 templates.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      FR-14 requires `WorkspaceLayoutWizard` to accept an optional `templateFilter` prop so that
      SpaarkeAi's `WorkspacePaneMenu` (task 032) can launch the wizard with a 6-template subset
      (`2-col-equal`, `3-row-mixed`, `hero-2x2`, `sidebar-main`, `single-column`, `single-column-5`),
      while the standalone LegalWorkspace continues to show all 9 templates. Per FR-25, the
      standalone LegalWorkspace must keep working identically ŌĆö making the prop optional with no
      default filter preserves backwards compatibility.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>src/solutions/WorkspaceLayoutWizard/src/App.tsx</file>
      <file>src/solutions/WorkspaceLayoutWizard/src/steps/TemplateStep.tsx</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-012">No shared-library changes here; the wizard stays in its existing package. The prop is additive.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-021">No new styling. Tokens compliance unaffected.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-022">React 19 typing ŌĆö use `React.FC` or the project's prop-typing convention. Use a typed `LayoutTemplateId` union, not a `string[]`.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-028">No new BFF calls.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">FR-25 backwards compatibility ŌĆö when `templateFilter` is absent, all 9 templates MUST remain selectable. NO default value other than `undefined`.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">FR-14 ŌĆö when `templateFilter` is present, only templates whose ID is in the array are rendered. Templates not in the array are filtered out (NOT disabled ŌĆö removed from the UI).</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">The prop is OPTIONAL. Do not change any callers (other than to document the new prop signature in a JSDoc comment).</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-012-shared-components.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-021-fluent-design-system.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-028-spaarke-auth-architecture.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r3/CLAUDE.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r3/spec.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r3/plan.md</file>
      <file>.claude/patterns/webresource/full-page-custom-page.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1" name="Read existing wizard structure">
      Open `src/solutions/WorkspaceLayoutWizard/src/App.tsx` and `steps/TemplateStep.tsx`. Identify
      where the template list is constructed (likely a const array of `LayoutTemplateId` entries).
      Capture the type alias `LayoutTemplateId` and the canonical 9-entry list.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Add templateFilter to props">
      In `TemplateStep.tsx` (or wherever the template list is consumed), add an optional prop
      `templateFilter?: LayoutTemplateId[]`. Type it precisely using the existing `LayoutTemplateId`
      union ŌĆö do NOT widen to `string[]`. Add a JSDoc comment explaining the intent and the
      FR-14 / FR-25 context.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Filter template list when prop present">
      Modify the rendering logic: if `templateFilter` is provided, filter the canonical 9-entry
      list to keep only entries whose ID is in `templateFilter`. If absent (`undefined`), render
      the full 9-entry list unchanged.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Plumb prop through App.tsx if needed">
      If `App.tsx` is the wizard's external entry point, add the same optional prop there and pass
      it down to `TemplateStep`. Match the existing prop-passing pattern of the wizard. Make sure
      there are no breaking changes to callers without the prop.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Verify all 9 templates still show when prop absent">
      Manually verify (or via the existing storybook / dev harness) that with no prop, the template
      list shows all 9 templates. This is the FR-25 backwards-compat invariant.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Add unit test for both paths">
      Add a unit test (or extend an existing test) that asserts:
      (a) Render `&lt;WorkspaceLayoutWizard /&gt;` with NO prop ŌåÆ all 9 templates rendered.
      (b) Render `&lt;WorkspaceLayoutWizard templateFilter={['2-col-equal','3-row-mixed','hero-2x2','sidebar-main','single-column','single-column-5']} /&gt;` ŌåÆ
          exactly 6 templates rendered, matching the IDs.
      Use the existing test harness conventions (find a sibling `*.test.tsx` for style reference).
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Build verification">
      Run `npm run build` (or the project's build command) in the WorkspaceLayoutWizard workspace.
      Confirm zero TypeScript errors and zero new lint warnings.
    </step>
    <step order="8" name="Update TASK-INDEX and commit">
      Update `projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r3/tasks/TASK-INDEX.md`: this task's status
      to Ō£ģ completed. Commit changes per project conventions.
    </step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool name="Read">Read App.tsx, TemplateStep.tsx</tool>
    <tool name="Edit">Add prop + filter logic; add test</tool>
    <tool name="Bash">npm build + test verification</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output type="code">src/solutions/WorkspaceLayoutWizard/src/steps/TemplateStep.tsx (modified ŌĆö adds templateFilter prop + filtering)</output>
    <output type="code">src/solutions/WorkspaceLayoutWizard/src/App.tsx (modified if prop plumbed through external API)</output>
    <output type="test">src/solutions/WorkspaceLayoutWizard/src/steps/TemplateStep.test.tsx (modified or new ŌĆö covers both paths)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">`WorkspaceLayoutWizard` (or its `TemplateStep`) accepts an optional `templateFilter?: LayoutTemplateId[]` prop typed against the existing `LayoutTemplateId` union.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">When `templateFilter` is absent (prop not passed), all 9 templates remain selectable ŌĆö backwards-compat invariant per FR-25 / NFR-10.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">When `templateFilter` is passed `['2-col-equal','3-row-mixed','hero-2x2','sidebar-main','single-column','single-column-5']`, exactly 6 templates render (the listed subset).</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Unit test exists and covers both paths (absent ŌåÆ 9 templates; present ŌåÆ 6 templates).</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`npm run build` succeeds with zero TypeScript errors and zero new lint warnings.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">No caller of `WorkspaceLayoutWizard` is broken ŌĆö all existing call sites (standalone LegalWorkspace) work unchanged because the prop is optional.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <ui-tests>
    <test name="Wizard Shows 6 Templates From SpaarkeAi, 9 From Standalone">
      <url>https://{org}.crm.dynamics.com/main.aspx?appid={app-id}&amp;pagetype=custom&amp;name=spaarke_spaarkeai</url>
      <steps>
        <step>Navigate to the SpaarkeAi code page</step>
        <step>Open WorkspacePaneMenu and click "+ New Workspace" (launches wizard with templateFilter)</step>
        <step>Count the templates rendered in the TemplateStep ŌĆö expect exactly 6</step>
        <step>Verify the 6 are: 2-col-equal, 3-row-mixed, hero-2x2, sidebar-main, single-column, single-column-5</step>
        <step>Close wizard. Open standalone LegalWorkspace code page in a separate tab.</step>
        <step>Launch its wizard (no `templateFilter`) and count ŌĆö expect all 9 templates</step>
        <step>Check console for JavaScript errors</step>
      </steps>
      <expected>SpaarkeAi wizard renders 6 templates; standalone LegalWorkspace wizard renders 9 templates. FR-25 backwards compat preserved.</expected>
    </test>

    <test name="Dark Mode Parity (ADR-021)">
      <steps>
        <step>Toggle dark mode in D365 settings</step>
        <step>Open wizard from SpaarkeAi (6-template view); verify dark-mode rendering</step>
        <step>Open wizard from standalone LegalWorkspace (9-template view); verify dark-mode rendering</step>
      </steps>
      <expected>Both wizard variants render correctly in dark mode. No hex-literal regressions introduced by the prop change.</expected>
    </test>
  </ui-tests>

  <execution>
